1
00:00:15,249 --> 00:00:17,651
(DEAN SPEAKING
IN THE DISTANCE)

2
00:00:19,420 --> 00:00:21,155
(KATHRYN GIGGLING)

3
00:00:28,096 --> 00:00:29,297
KATHRYN: We're gonna sink!

4
00:00:30,231 --> 00:00:31,799
TOM: Could you move?

5
00:00:31,832 --> 00:00:34,435
DEAN: ...strive to ensure
the blessings

6
00:00:34,468 --> 00:00:37,271
of the law to our society.

7
00:00:38,706 --> 00:00:42,343
Today, you join them
in their task.

8
00:00:42,376 --> 00:00:44,378
You have learned the law.

9
00:00:45,213 --> 00:00:46,314
Where is she?

10
00:00:46,347 --> 00:00:48,116
DEAN: But what must
sustain you now,

11
00:00:48,149 --> 00:00:52,720
is the moral code
from which it
springs.

12
00:00:52,753 --> 00:00:54,855
(ALL APPLAUDING)

13
00:00:54,888 --> 00:00:56,790
KATHRYN: (WHISPERING)
Oh, my God! Look!

14
00:00:57,725 --> 00:00:59,427
Oh, my God,
they finished!

15
00:00:59,460 --> 00:01:00,828
(BOTH MUMBLING)

16
00:01:01,729 --> 00:01:03,131
DEAN: Brian Adams.

17
00:01:03,164 --> 00:01:05,433
TOM: Thanks, it was
good for me, too.

18
00:01:07,835 --> 00:01:09,503
-Quiet, or they'll see us.
(KATHRYN EXCLAIMS)

19
00:01:09,537 --> 00:01:11,505
KATHRYN: Don't splash me!
TOM: I'm doing
the best I can!

20
00:01:11,539 --> 00:01:14,275
KATHRYN: My mother
is gonna kill me
if I miss this thing.

21
00:01:14,308 --> 00:01:15,709
(SIGHS)

22
00:01:15,743 --> 00:01:18,112
How could
she do this to me?

23
00:01:18,146 --> 00:01:20,214
Oh! There she is.
There she is!

24
00:01:21,715 --> 00:01:24,118
Almost, almost! Ah!

25
00:01:27,255 --> 00:01:28,489
(YELPS)

26
00:01:30,158 --> 00:01:31,559
KATHRYN: Your hat!
Your hat! Your hat!

27
00:01:34,762 --> 00:01:36,230
(BOTH SCREAM)

28
00:01:36,264 --> 00:01:38,499
(GASPS) Don't fall in!
Don't...

29
00:01:44,572 --> 00:01:46,240
(WHISPERS) Get your shoe!

30
00:01:52,346 --> 00:01:54,182
This is so embarrassing.

31
00:01:54,215 --> 00:01:56,317
Nobody's looking
at you, dear.

32
00:01:57,851 --> 00:01:59,387
DEAN: James Seller.

33
00:02:01,489 --> 00:02:03,157
Jay Circa.

34
00:02:05,593 --> 00:02:09,330
PRIEST: Do you,
Thomas Ainsworth,
take Kathryn McClain

35
00:02:09,363 --> 00:02:11,499
to be your
lawfully wedded wife...
(SOBBING)

36
00:02:11,532 --> 00:02:13,434
To hold and to cherish

37
00:02:13,467 --> 00:02:17,405
in sickness and in health,
until death do you part?

38
00:02:17,438 --> 00:02:19,473
Yeah, I...
Yeah, I guess so.

39
00:02:19,507 --> 00:02:20,708
(SOBS)

40
00:02:23,477 --> 00:02:26,847
I, I just don't, you know,
I don't want to back her
into a corner...

41
00:02:26,880 --> 00:02:28,482
(SOBBING CONTINUES)

42
00:02:29,950 --> 00:02:32,320
Look, Kat,
I want to marry you

43
00:02:32,353 --> 00:02:35,556
but it doesn't feel right
if it's forced.

44
00:02:35,589 --> 00:02:39,593
I never didn't want to,
and why wouldn't I want to
less now?

45
00:02:41,329 --> 00:02:42,430
Huh?

46
00:02:43,664 --> 00:02:46,334
That was a little
less than clear.

47
00:02:46,367 --> 00:02:49,270
Look, Kat, I love you,
I'll do my part...
Unless you've decided that...

48
00:02:50,871 --> 00:02:52,240
You...

49
00:02:57,478 --> 00:02:58,646
I love you, too.

50
00:03:02,283 --> 00:03:04,184
I absolutely want to.

51
00:03:06,420 --> 00:03:07,488
I do.

52
00:03:08,489 --> 00:03:10,658
It's his turn.

53
00:03:10,691 --> 00:03:12,260
It's your turn.

54
00:03:15,363 --> 00:03:17,231
Oh, yeah, I do, too.

55
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:22,836
Notch me, Daddy,
notch me.
(DOORBELL RINGS)

56
00:03:22,870 --> 00:03:24,972
Just a minute, Mother.

57
00:03:25,005 --> 00:03:26,307
Tom?

58
00:03:27,741 --> 00:03:29,743
Hold on, honey,
Mom will get it.

59
00:03:30,611 --> 00:03:31,812
(DOORBELL RINGS)

60
00:03:31,845 --> 00:03:33,281
Okay, darling.

61
00:03:33,314 --> 00:03:35,849
Stand up straight.
Stand up straight, honey.

62
00:03:35,883 --> 00:03:37,951
That's it, perfect.

63
00:03:37,985 --> 00:03:40,721
I got it. Now go open
the door for Mamaw,
and Mom will write the date.

64
00:03:40,754 --> 00:03:42,490
Go on, honey.

65
00:03:42,523 --> 00:03:43,957
(RINGING CONTINUES)

66
00:03:43,991 --> 00:03:46,026
Tom, you need to get
your stuff out of there.

67
00:03:46,059 --> 00:03:47,761
Mom has to set up
for Mikey's party.

68
00:03:47,795 --> 00:03:50,731
Hey there,
little birthday boy.

69
00:03:50,764 --> 00:03:52,600
Ooh!

70
00:03:52,633 --> 00:03:54,968
How does it feel
to be four?

71
00:03:55,002 --> 00:03:56,404
Big.
Oh. (CHUCKLES)

72
00:03:56,437 --> 00:03:59,407
KATHRYN: I'll be done
with these depositions
and back here by five.

73
00:03:59,440 --> 00:04:01,642
Did you pick up
the C-A-K-E?

74
00:04:01,675 --> 00:04:03,511
Cake, Mommy?
(LAUGHING) Oh, cute.

75
00:04:03,544 --> 00:04:05,579
Tom? Tom?

76
00:04:05,613 --> 00:04:07,348
Mmm. What?

77
00:04:07,381 --> 00:04:08,416
Did you get the cake?

78
00:04:09,683 --> 00:04:10,784
Ugh!

79
00:04:12,085 --> 00:04:14,855
(EXHALES)

80
00:04:14,888 --> 00:04:17,758
Honey, I'm trying to keep
these kids out of jail,
they're counting on me.

81
00:04:17,791 --> 00:04:19,993
Maybe Mikey should
get himself arrested.

82
00:04:21,462 --> 00:04:22,363
I'm going to be
back really soon

83
00:04:22,396 --> 00:04:24,432
and we're going to have
a great party, okay?

84
00:04:24,465 --> 00:04:27,067
Okay. See you soon!

85
00:04:27,100 --> 00:04:29,437
Let's get ready for
your birthday party.

86
00:04:34,508 --> 00:04:35,909
(KNOCKING)

87
00:04:35,943 --> 00:04:37,445
It's open.

88
00:04:42,383 --> 00:04:44,752
I don't know why
I ever bother
to give you a day off.

89
00:04:44,785 --> 00:04:47,821
Hi, Benjamin.
Remember Daryl Cook?

90
00:04:47,855 --> 00:04:49,723
You defended him.

91
00:04:49,757 --> 00:04:52,460
Convenience store,
threatened the clerk
with a jar of acid.

92
00:04:52,493 --> 00:04:53,827
Which turned out
to be apple juice.

93
00:04:53,861 --> 00:04:55,563
Well, he used
a gun this time.

94
00:04:55,596 --> 00:04:57,765
He's been bounced
out of juvy into adult.

95
00:04:57,798 --> 00:05:00,901
Biggest idiot craze since
the hula-hoop.

96
00:05:00,934 --> 00:05:03,070
Well, what do you
want me to work on,
Mincey or the kid?

97
00:05:03,103 --> 00:05:05,839
I want you to argue it.
It's already on the calendar.

98
00:05:08,075 --> 00:05:10,778
Okay. Whose court is it?

99
00:05:10,811 --> 00:05:11,912
Marion Hopkins.

100
00:05:12,746 --> 00:05:14,548
I can handle that.

101
00:05:15,483 --> 00:05:16,884
Oh, come on Marion.

102
00:05:16,917 --> 00:05:20,654
Since when did Morris
ever invite you to anything
more than lunch?

103
00:05:20,688 --> 00:05:22,723
After a few months,
things move along.

104
00:05:22,756 --> 00:05:25,559
You'd know that if
you ever dated anyone
more than twice.

105
00:05:25,593 --> 00:05:29,863
Well, what kind of date
can you possibly have
on a Monday morning?

106
00:05:29,897 --> 00:05:31,832
He's taking me to his cabin.

107
00:05:31,865 --> 00:05:34,868
Cabin? That's not a date,
that's a proposal.

108
00:05:34,902 --> 00:05:37,605
Well, I don't want to have him
drive me back
on Sunday night.

109
00:05:37,638 --> 00:05:39,707
Well then,
take two cars.

110
00:05:39,740 --> 00:05:41,909
Oh, come on, Kathryn.

111
00:05:41,942 --> 00:05:44,745
I know your calendar's
clear on Monday, I checked.

112
00:05:44,778 --> 00:05:46,447
Look, I'm having
Thanksgiving
at your mother's.

113
00:05:46,480 --> 00:05:47,648
That's got to be
worth something.

114
00:05:47,681 --> 00:05:49,550
I mean,
one case, Kathryn!

115
00:05:50,718 --> 00:05:52,152
KATHRYN: Are you sure
it was 11?

116
00:05:52,185 --> 00:05:53,921
SYLVIA: Of course I'm sure.

117
00:05:53,954 --> 00:05:57,491
Eleven was the perfect fit,
I measured it.

118
00:05:57,525 --> 00:06:00,160
KATHRYN: But did you
count the bushes
when you put them in?

119
00:06:00,193 --> 00:06:02,396
Because the nursery
could have miscounted them.

120
00:06:02,430 --> 00:06:07,535
Florence planted a single
azalea at the end of her
driveway the next day!

121
00:06:07,568 --> 00:06:10,538
Mother, you know as well
as I do you can't
swing a cat in this city

122
00:06:10,571 --> 00:06:11,672
without hitting an azalea.

123
00:06:11,705 --> 00:06:16,510
All I know is I had 11,
now I have 10.

124
00:06:16,544 --> 00:06:19,747
And she has one.
Well, did you say
something to her?

125
00:06:19,780 --> 00:06:22,883
I can't accuse
the minister's wife
of stealing.

126
00:06:23,917 --> 00:06:25,586
We could go get it back.

127
00:06:25,619 --> 00:06:26,754
Don't encourage her.

128
00:06:26,787 --> 00:06:28,622
SYLVIA: Dinner is served now.

129
00:06:28,656 --> 00:06:31,124
It will be absolutely
ruined cold.

130
00:06:31,158 --> 00:06:33,126
What's with all the tags?

131
00:06:33,160 --> 00:06:35,763
She started doing that
when Dad died.

132
00:06:35,796 --> 00:06:37,798
She started putting
tags on everything,

133
00:06:37,831 --> 00:06:39,867
telling who was
going to get what.

134
00:06:39,900 --> 00:06:42,703
I call it the museum
of the soon to be dead.

135
00:06:42,736 --> 00:06:45,005
(LAUGHING) You've got
to be kidding.

136
00:06:45,038 --> 00:06:46,840
You'll thank me
when the time comes

137
00:06:46,874 --> 00:06:49,977
and there'll be no tough
decisions to make.

138
00:06:50,010 --> 00:06:51,779
Whenever I give her
a Christmas present,

139
00:06:51,812 --> 00:06:53,847
I wonder if I should
tag it twice.

140
00:06:54,482 --> 00:06:55,883
Who's Charlotte?

141
00:06:55,916 --> 00:06:58,051
A second cousin
once removed.

142
00:06:58,085 --> 00:06:59,920
Beautiful decanter.

143
00:07:01,822 --> 00:07:02,956
Damn.

144
00:07:04,257 --> 00:07:06,126
There you go, Daryl.

145
00:07:07,027 --> 00:07:08,529
Happy Thanksgiving.

146
00:07:14,968 --> 00:07:17,104
So, who's Mikey?

147
00:07:18,071 --> 00:07:20,040
Who?
The notches?

148
00:07:23,276 --> 00:07:24,545
Oh.

149
00:07:25,045 --> 00:07:26,113
Um...

150
00:07:27,080 --> 00:07:29,149
Michael. He's my son.

151
00:07:32,620 --> 00:07:34,054
Where's he at?

152
00:07:36,890 --> 00:07:38,492
I don't know.

153
00:07:44,765 --> 00:07:47,200
(DOG BARKING)

154
00:07:47,234 --> 00:07:48,936
Michael, I can...
I can wait in the car.

155
00:07:48,969 --> 00:07:50,571
Good afternoon, Mr. Otto.

156
00:07:51,572 --> 00:07:52,940
What?

157
00:07:52,973 --> 00:07:54,975
I just don't see any point
in rocking the boat.

158
00:07:55,008 --> 00:07:56,710
You're such a coward.

159
00:07:57,878 --> 00:08:01,114
Otto! I have guests!

160
00:08:01,148 --> 00:08:03,083
Oh, I'm going to take
my hedge clipper

161
00:08:03,116 --> 00:08:05,886
to that little overactive
piece of vegetation

162
00:08:05,919 --> 00:08:08,756
if you don't shut him up!

163
00:08:08,789 --> 00:08:10,924
Happy Thanksgiving, Sylvia!

164
00:08:10,958 --> 00:08:12,125
(SIGHS)

165
00:08:13,226 --> 00:08:14,795
Oh.

166
00:08:14,828 --> 00:08:16,630
Mikey!
Mamaw.

167
00:08:16,664 --> 00:08:20,033
Oh! I thought you'd
dropped off the planet.

168
00:08:20,067 --> 00:08:21,702
Oh, never mind.

169
00:08:21,735 --> 00:08:23,837
You're just in time,
there's plenty of turkey.

170
00:08:23,871 --> 00:08:25,939
Oh, it's so good
to see you.

171
00:08:27,340 --> 00:08:29,743
I see
you've brought a stray.
We should have called.

172
00:08:29,777 --> 00:08:33,714
Oh, I always take in strays
for the holidays, you know,

173
00:08:33,747 --> 00:08:35,515
there but for the grace
of God.

174
00:08:39,052 --> 00:08:41,855
Michael.
Hey, Mom.

175
00:08:41,889 --> 00:08:43,924
Mamaw didn't tell me
you were coming.

176
00:08:43,957 --> 00:08:46,293
Yeah, well,
it was impulse.

177
00:08:47,160 --> 00:08:48,195
Hi, Mrs. Ainsworth.

178
00:08:49,897 --> 00:08:51,632
Name's McClain.

179
00:08:51,665 --> 00:08:54,735
She uses her maiden name,
isn't that retro?

180
00:08:58,071 --> 00:09:02,042
I'm sorry.
Mother, this is Bruce.

181
00:09:02,075 --> 00:09:05,613
Bruce, Mother.
Hello, Mother McClain.

182
00:09:05,646 --> 00:09:07,247
It's nice to finally
meet you, Bruce.

183
00:09:07,280 --> 00:09:08,982
Make room, make room.

184
00:09:10,951 --> 00:09:12,152
Well...

185
00:09:16,790 --> 00:09:20,027
All rise, the Honorable Judge
Kathryn McClain presiding.

186
00:09:25,332 --> 00:09:26,667
(DOOR SLAMS)

187
00:09:29,870 --> 00:09:31,739
(WHISPERING) Marion,
I'm going to kill you.

188
00:09:34,374 --> 00:09:37,144
You may be seated.

189
00:09:37,177 --> 00:09:39,312
Case on call,
 Estate vs. Daryl Cook.

190
00:09:40,914 --> 00:09:43,383
Prosecution,
are you ready?
Yes, Your Honor.

191
00:09:43,416 --> 00:09:45,886
Defense, you ready?
Yes, but I have a motion.

192
00:09:45,919 --> 00:09:47,087
What's the motion?

193
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:48,622
Move to dismiss.

194
00:09:48,656 --> 00:09:50,290
Grounds?

195
00:09:50,323 --> 00:09:53,260
My client is a juvenile
and it's a direct violation of
his constitutional rights

196
00:09:53,293 --> 00:09:57,030
to be tried in an adult
court where his identity
is known to the public.

197
00:09:57,064 --> 00:09:58,799
Council, I think
you know that
as a juvenile,

198
00:09:58,832 --> 00:10:01,268
your client has no such
constitutional rights.

199
00:10:01,301 --> 00:10:03,170
I suggest you move on to
something more relevant.

200
00:10:03,203 --> 00:10:04,705
With all due respect,
Your Honor,

201
00:10:04,738 --> 00:10:06,239
I really shouldn't need
an opening argument

202
00:10:06,273 --> 00:10:08,241
for a case that
shouldn't be in this court.

203
00:10:08,275 --> 00:10:09,910
Nevertheless,
I suggest you find one

204
00:10:09,943 --> 00:10:13,714
because in two seconds,
the prosecution
will have the floor.

205
00:10:13,747 --> 00:10:15,749
Your Honor, may I
approach the bench?
No.

206
00:10:15,783 --> 00:10:17,084
Your Honor, I...
(GAVEL THUDS)

207
00:10:17,117 --> 00:10:19,653
This court is adjourned for
15 minutes.

208
00:10:19,687 --> 00:10:21,822
Council,
in my chambers, please.

209
00:10:27,094 --> 00:10:28,996
You should stay in
juvenile court, Tom,

210
00:10:29,029 --> 00:10:31,264
you have so much
in common with your clients.
Oh, really?

211
00:10:31,298 --> 00:10:35,035
I see what you mean.
Patronized, marginalized,
ignored by the system.

212
00:10:35,068 --> 00:10:37,905
Have I left anything out?

213
00:10:37,938 --> 00:10:41,842
Look, why would you
bring this hopeless case
into my court?

214
00:10:41,875 --> 00:10:43,143
I thought it was Marion's.

215
00:10:43,176 --> 00:10:46,446
It was scheduled...
Get continuance,
massage your calendar.

216
00:10:46,479 --> 00:10:49,082
Unless, of course, you wanted
to argue in front of me.
I don't know.

217
00:10:49,116 --> 00:10:51,885
Maybe try to take advantage
of some personal
relationship which,

218
00:10:51,919 --> 00:10:54,154
by the way,
hasn't existed in
over a decade.

219
00:10:54,187 --> 00:10:55,455
That would be...

220
00:10:55,488 --> 00:10:57,390
I don't suppose
it would cross your mind
that I wanted to be here

221
00:10:57,424 --> 00:10:59,392
because I respect you
as a judge.

222
00:10:59,426 --> 00:11:01,862
I don't think that...
What is it about this kid
that has you so worked up?

223
00:11:03,831 --> 00:11:06,333
Somebody's got to
cover the fringes.

224
00:11:06,366 --> 00:11:08,201
Not all of us can be at
the center of the universe.

225
00:11:08,235 --> 00:11:10,738
It's already
too damn crowded.
Your Honor!

226
00:11:10,771 --> 00:11:12,773
BOTH: What?

227
00:11:12,806 --> 00:11:14,908
The people would
understand a continuance

228
00:11:14,942 --> 00:11:16,343
if you'd like to
recuse yourself.

229
00:11:16,376 --> 00:11:17,410
I mean...

230
00:11:21,181 --> 00:11:22,249
Is there a bathroom?

231
00:11:24,484 --> 00:11:25,953
Kathryn...

232
00:11:25,986 --> 00:11:27,120
(DOOR OPENS)

233
00:11:27,154 --> 00:11:29,456
This kids has had
a nightmare life.

234
00:11:29,489 --> 00:11:31,725
Sell the jury on the merits,

235
00:11:31,759 --> 00:11:34,995
but leave out the
constitutional acrobatics.
All right.

236
00:11:35,028 --> 00:11:38,231
I keep forgetting
how damn inconvenient
you find the constitution.

237
00:11:38,265 --> 00:11:40,067
Oh, God,
this is so typical.

238
00:11:40,100 --> 00:11:43,070
Yeah, well,
this is so typical of you.

239
00:11:43,103 --> 00:11:45,272
(KNOCKING)
Uh, Your Honor?

240
00:11:46,406 --> 00:11:47,841
Come in.

241
00:11:59,019 --> 00:12:01,354
Listen, catch Judge McClain
before she leaves
and give that to her.

242
00:12:03,523 --> 00:12:05,325
Hey, everybody.
Hey.

243
00:12:05,358 --> 00:12:06,794
Hey.

244
00:12:06,827 --> 00:12:11,364
Well, Marion, I hope
your weekend was worth it
because you are dead.

245
00:12:11,398 --> 00:12:13,400
Haven't you guys ever
run into each other before?

246
00:12:13,433 --> 00:12:14,935
It's not that big a town.

247
00:12:14,968 --> 00:12:17,004
You must still have
some friends in common.

248
00:12:17,037 --> 00:12:19,539
Are you kidding?
Divorce is like
cell division.

249
00:12:19,572 --> 00:12:22,342
First the nucleus splits
and then all those
chromosomes thingies

250
00:12:22,375 --> 00:12:25,178
swim off to one side
or the other. It's science.

251
00:12:25,212 --> 00:12:27,180
(ALL LAUGHING)

252
00:12:27,214 --> 00:12:29,549
Excuse me, I was asked
to give this to you.

253
00:12:29,582 --> 00:12:31,184
I bet it's from
Daniel Klein.

254
00:12:31,218 --> 00:12:34,822
Poor boy has no idea what
he's getting himself into.

255
00:12:34,855 --> 00:12:36,990
You're just jealous
because I made the list
for court of appeal.

256
00:12:37,024 --> 00:12:38,859
Don't try and
change the subject.

257
00:12:38,892 --> 00:12:40,127
Since when was Tom a subject?

258
00:12:40,160 --> 00:12:42,262
I thought I was talking
about Daniel.

259
00:12:42,295 --> 00:12:44,832
Come on, open it.
Get a life, you guys.

260
00:12:44,865 --> 00:12:46,766
Why? We've got yours.

261
00:12:48,268 --> 00:12:51,538
Oh! Oh, hello!

262
00:12:51,571 --> 00:12:53,173
If you don't sleep
with him, honey,

263
00:12:53,206 --> 00:12:55,008
you could certainly
sleep with this.

264
00:12:55,042 --> 00:12:57,577
Give me that, you slut.
Speaking of which,
Morris is very lonely.

265
00:12:57,610 --> 00:12:59,512
Morris is a troll.
(ALL LAUGHING)

266
00:12:59,546 --> 00:13:02,115
So, uh, the cabin.
Oh, don't.

267
00:13:02,149 --> 00:13:03,416
(ALL LAUGHING)

268
00:13:04,852 --> 00:13:07,120
You know, it's not that
I was nervous about it,

269
00:13:07,154 --> 00:13:10,490
I just couldn't figure out
how we'd get past
the work situation.

270
00:13:10,523 --> 00:13:13,093
Because no matter
how we feel,

271
00:13:13,126 --> 00:13:16,196
you still have to put that
robe on every day.

272
00:13:16,229 --> 00:13:18,832
It's the robe, isn't it?
I knew it was the robe.

273
00:13:18,866 --> 00:13:21,101
Do you keep one here?

274
00:13:21,134 --> 00:13:22,235
Please tell me
you're not kinky

275
00:13:22,269 --> 00:13:25,305
because I've got so far to go
before I get to kinky.

276
00:13:27,374 --> 00:13:29,042
Can I kiss you?

277
00:13:30,443 --> 00:13:32,245
Mmm. Sure.

278
00:13:43,323 --> 00:13:44,524
(GASPS)

279
00:13:45,025 --> 00:13:46,359
What?

280
00:13:46,393 --> 00:13:47,527
What?

281
00:13:47,560 --> 00:13:49,462
Sorry. I'm sorry.

282
00:13:49,496 --> 00:13:51,031
That's okay.
I hope you didn't think
I was being too forward.

283
00:13:51,064 --> 00:13:52,432
No, I didn't think,
no, not at all.

284
00:13:52,465 --> 00:13:53,867
Because I don't
want you to think
I'm just...

285
00:13:53,901 --> 00:13:55,235
No, I don't think that.

286
00:13:57,204 --> 00:13:58,605
I could help you
clean up the kitchen.
I...

287
00:13:58,638 --> 00:14:01,474
Do you want me to
clean up the kitchen?
No, the...

288
00:14:01,508 --> 00:14:04,277
Actually that, I,
that was ordered in.

289
00:14:04,311 --> 00:14:05,879
Really? Oh.
Yes.

290
00:14:07,380 --> 00:14:09,249
I should go.
It's okay, you don't
have to go.

291
00:14:09,282 --> 00:14:12,519
I know. I just,
I think we should
try this tomorrow.

292
00:14:12,552 --> 00:14:14,354
We could try it tomorrow.
Yeah.

293
00:14:14,387 --> 00:14:15,555
Is it too soon?
No, no, no.

294
00:14:15,588 --> 00:14:17,057
Okay.

295
00:14:17,090 --> 00:14:18,525
Call me?
Yeah.

296
00:14:42,015 --> 00:14:43,116
(GRUNTS)

297
00:15:17,317 --> 00:15:19,652
So, Irish,

298
00:15:19,686 --> 00:15:22,922
just which part of
my total remission
wasn't total?

299
00:15:24,757 --> 00:15:29,029
Kathryn, cancer is
a vicious disease,

300
00:15:29,062 --> 00:15:31,031
and it doesn't usually
play fair.

301
00:15:31,064 --> 00:15:34,634
Oh, not fair.
Well, my my.

302
00:15:34,667 --> 00:15:37,504
I guess it's time
for the gloves
to come off, hmm?

303
00:15:38,571 --> 00:15:39,639
So...

304
00:15:40,573 --> 00:15:42,509
What do we do now?

305
00:15:42,542 --> 00:15:44,011
We start again?

306
00:15:44,044 --> 00:15:49,282
Listen, another round
of the same sequence
will do absolutely no good.

307
00:15:55,355 --> 00:15:57,490
What then?

308
00:15:57,524 --> 00:16:00,160
There's a research
hospital in Houston.

309
00:16:00,193 --> 00:16:03,130
Cutting edge young Turks
with all the new drugs.

310
00:16:03,163 --> 00:16:06,666
Big clinical tests
with promising results,
all that.

311
00:16:06,699 --> 00:16:08,635
Tests?

312
00:16:08,668 --> 00:16:10,437
Doesn't that mean
I could get a placebo?

313
00:16:10,470 --> 00:16:11,704
Do you know
these doctors?

314
00:16:11,738 --> 00:16:13,540
Yes.

315
00:16:13,573 --> 00:16:16,176
They're every bit as good
as they think they are.

316
00:16:17,510 --> 00:16:20,647
Hmm.
Sounds like a nightmare.

317
00:16:20,680 --> 00:16:22,082
Nothing you can't handle.

318
00:16:24,817 --> 00:16:26,719
It's Daniel, isn't it?
(CHUCKLES)

319
00:16:26,753 --> 00:16:29,189
How did he get to be
so serious?

320
00:16:29,222 --> 00:16:31,324
Oh, come on, why do you
have to be so secretive.

321
00:16:31,358 --> 00:16:33,293
Can't you at least tell me
where you're going?

322
00:16:33,326 --> 00:16:35,428
Cruise? Mountains?

323
00:16:35,462 --> 00:16:36,629
Both.

324
00:16:36,663 --> 00:16:40,067
Daryl Cook, he's 16.

325
00:16:40,100 --> 00:16:42,702
The facts were tried,
the sentencing guidelines
are as clear as a bell.

326
00:16:42,735 --> 00:16:45,105
No, they're not,
they're rigid.

327
00:16:45,138 --> 00:16:47,707
And the boy
has a good lawyer,
he'll appeal.

328
00:16:47,740 --> 00:16:52,112
Anything special you
want me to say to Tom
when I deliver this?

329
00:16:52,145 --> 00:16:54,581
Well, you'll think
of something.

330
00:16:54,614 --> 00:16:58,118
So my mother calls me,
says can you feed the cats
for five days.

331
00:16:58,151 --> 00:17:00,520
I cancel my cases,
go to Texas

332
00:17:00,553 --> 00:17:03,790
and she waits till
I'm knee deep in
choice cuts and cheese bits

333
00:17:03,823 --> 00:17:05,725
to mention that there's
a little cancer thing...
What?

334
00:17:05,758 --> 00:17:06,793
...she needs
to take care of.

335
00:17:06,826 --> 00:17:08,328
How did that get in there?
They hate that stuff.

336
00:17:08,361 --> 00:17:10,630
What am I supposed
to say to that, huh?

337
00:17:10,663 --> 00:17:12,365
Oh, cancer.
Wet food or dry food?

338
00:17:12,399 --> 00:17:16,336
Michael, can you make sure
you change the litter because
I don't care what they say,

339
00:17:16,369 --> 00:17:19,606
if you scoop, the whole place
is going to smell like a barn
by the time I get back.

340
00:17:19,639 --> 00:17:21,374
I'm just curious, Mom.

341
00:17:21,408 --> 00:17:24,244
If the chemo had worked
and you didn't
need a cat-sitter,

342
00:17:24,277 --> 00:17:25,612
would you have even
mentioned it to me?

343
00:17:25,645 --> 00:17:28,115
There was no need
to worry anybody.

344
00:17:28,148 --> 00:17:29,616
Are my vitamins there?

345
00:17:29,649 --> 00:17:32,119
Please.
What else do I live for?

346
00:17:33,286 --> 00:17:35,388
Mamaw, it's her career.

347
00:17:35,422 --> 00:17:37,090
Michael, I know
it's a lot to ask,

348
00:17:37,124 --> 00:17:40,227
but do you think
you could come by
twice a day

349
00:17:40,260 --> 00:17:43,430
because Archibald
gets bloated if he eats
too much at once,

350
00:17:43,463 --> 00:17:44,664
and Mehitabel...

351
00:17:44,697 --> 00:17:46,466
You did tell her?

352
00:17:51,704 --> 00:17:55,242
My God.
Don't I feel special.

353
00:17:55,275 --> 00:17:57,544
I know and Mamaw doesn't?

354
00:17:57,577 --> 00:17:59,379
What am I supposed
to do with that?

355
00:18:02,182 --> 00:18:03,483
Feed the cats.

356
00:18:03,516 --> 00:18:04,817
Great.

357
00:18:04,851 --> 00:18:07,354
If you die,
can I mention it to her?

358
00:18:07,387 --> 00:18:09,556
(LAUGHING) Michael.

359
00:18:09,589 --> 00:18:13,260
Come on, don't get
so dramatic on me.

360
00:18:13,293 --> 00:18:17,730
Anyway, what would be
so scary about
going to heaven?

361
00:18:17,764 --> 00:18:20,367
Besides the fact that
you don't believe in it?

362
00:18:21,434 --> 00:18:25,338
I am not going to die.

363
00:18:25,372 --> 00:18:29,309
Dr. Hurley, he's going
to make sure that
I don't get the placebo.

364
00:18:29,342 --> 00:18:32,245
Besides,
disease is a state of mind

365
00:18:33,280 --> 00:18:36,183
and any mind
can be changed.

366
00:18:36,216 --> 00:18:38,251
I just haven't found
the right argument yet.

367
00:18:42,855 --> 00:18:45,725
Think I can
get a retrial based on
her hating your guts?

368
00:18:45,758 --> 00:18:48,828
Just the first step, Daryl.
We have to work our way
up the ladder.

369
00:18:48,861 --> 00:18:51,864
Marion, what happened,
where's Kathryn?

370
00:18:51,898 --> 00:18:53,200
You don't want to know.

371
00:18:53,233 --> 00:18:55,535
Yes, I do want to know.
Why wasn't she here
for the verdict?

372
00:19:00,707 --> 00:19:03,743
Sarah, when is
Judge McClain
back in court?

373
00:19:03,776 --> 00:19:06,413
She's cleared her calendar
for the rest of the week.

374
00:19:19,592 --> 00:19:21,328
(DOORBELL RINGS)

375
00:19:29,402 --> 00:19:30,637
Michael.

376
00:19:32,239 --> 00:19:33,573
(CAT MEOWS)

377
00:19:37,777 --> 00:19:39,312
It's good to see you.

378
00:19:41,881 --> 00:19:44,517
I need to talk
to your mother.
She's not home.

379
00:19:44,551 --> 00:19:46,586
When will she be back?
I'm not her secretary.

380
00:19:46,619 --> 00:19:47,720
Michael.

381
00:19:49,356 --> 00:19:50,923
This is important.

382
00:19:50,957 --> 00:19:52,559
Do you mind if I wait?

383
00:19:54,494 --> 00:19:55,628
Did somebody say martinis?

384
00:19:58,598 --> 00:20:01,568
She's not going
to be back for three days,
you can wait by the pool.

385
00:20:01,601 --> 00:20:02,835
Look...
There's a pool?

386
00:20:02,869 --> 00:20:06,973
Your mother is carrying
half a pharmacy
in her handbag.

387
00:20:07,006 --> 00:20:09,376
She has never missed
a day in court

388
00:20:09,409 --> 00:20:13,646
and now all of a sudden
she's cleared her calendar
for a week.

389
00:20:13,680 --> 00:20:16,483
Please, I want to know
what's going on.

390
00:20:18,985 --> 00:20:20,787
Don't let the cat out.

391
00:20:30,697 --> 00:20:32,399
I'm Tom.

392
00:20:32,432 --> 00:20:34,334
I'm Bruce,
it's nice to meet you.

393
00:20:34,367 --> 00:20:35,402
It's nice to meet you, too.

394
00:20:37,937 --> 00:20:40,840
I, uh, understand
she throws up a lot.

395
00:20:55,755 --> 00:20:58,525
Wonder if the Astros are
gonna sign the pitcher
from Cuba.

396
00:21:00,427 --> 00:21:02,395
What are the papers
saying about it in Houston?

397
00:21:02,429 --> 00:21:05,398
I wouldn't know.
I put my money
on the Jets.

398
00:21:05,432 --> 00:21:07,567
Well, that's football
and that's New York.

399
00:21:08,100 --> 00:21:10,470
Football, baseball.

400
00:21:10,503 --> 00:21:13,673
The shapes may be different
but they're still just balls.

401
00:21:13,706 --> 00:21:15,908
Kathryn!
What? Oh!

402
00:21:16,876 --> 00:21:18,711
Who's he, your florist?

403
00:21:18,745 --> 00:21:21,548
Oh, Tom, what are
you doing here?

404
00:21:21,581 --> 00:21:23,350
I thought you might
want some help.

405
00:21:23,383 --> 00:21:24,584
Who gave you that idea?

406
00:21:24,617 --> 00:21:28,455
Oh, I think
his name was Bruce,
as in Michael's Bruce.

407
00:21:28,488 --> 00:21:29,889
Go away, Tom.

408
00:21:31,891 --> 00:21:33,693
Kat, why didn't you
tell me you were sick?

409
00:21:33,726 --> 00:21:35,595
Because it's none
of your business.

410
00:21:35,628 --> 00:21:36,663
But it's his business?

411
00:21:36,696 --> 00:21:38,465
It's none of your business
whose business it is.

412
00:21:38,498 --> 00:21:40,600
Don't you have
a plane to catch?
Mmm-hmm.

413
00:21:40,633 --> 00:21:41,868
To your funeral.

414
00:21:41,901 --> 00:21:44,404
Nobody knows,
including you.

415
00:21:44,437 --> 00:21:46,539
I have a career
to protect.

416
00:21:46,573 --> 00:21:48,775
Besides,
it'll all be over soon.

417
00:21:48,808 --> 00:21:52,912
And the worst problem
I should have is explaining
a ridiculously short hairdo.

418
00:21:54,481 --> 00:21:56,416
Hey, sweetheart!

419
00:21:56,749 --> 00:21:57,850
Mmm!

420
00:21:58,618 --> 00:21:59,852
How was D.C.?

421
00:21:59,886 --> 00:22:02,422
Dismal without you.

422
00:22:02,455 --> 00:22:04,090
Daniel,
have you met my hu...

423
00:22:04,123 --> 00:22:05,592
Have you met
Tom Ainsworth?

424
00:22:05,625 --> 00:22:08,528
No, haven't had
the pleasure, Tom.
Thanks.

425
00:22:08,561 --> 00:22:13,633
Well, got to get our little
traveler back home for
a hot tub and a back rub.

426
00:22:13,666 --> 00:22:14,967
We'll see you later.

427
00:22:20,006 --> 00:22:22,409
WOMAN: (ON PA)
 Ladies and gentleman, 
 we are overbooked.

428
00:22:22,442 --> 00:22:24,644
Flight 282 to Toronto...

429
00:22:47,800 --> 00:22:48,901
Wow.

430
00:22:50,437 --> 00:22:51,971
Was that for me?

431
00:23:45,525 --> 00:23:48,895
(CAT MEOWING)
Oh, look at you.

432
00:23:48,928 --> 00:23:52,031
Oh, sweetie pie, ooh.

433
00:23:52,064 --> 00:23:54,667
Want a little milk?
Wouldn't that be nice?

434
00:23:56,569 --> 00:23:59,205
Yes, a little drink of milk.

435
00:23:59,238 --> 00:24:01,107
That'll be good, won't it?

436
00:24:01,140 --> 00:24:03,142
Yeah, that'll...

437
00:24:03,175 --> 00:24:05,578
That'll taste good.

438
00:24:05,612 --> 00:24:07,246
Here we go.

439
00:24:07,279 --> 00:24:08,581
Mmm.

440
00:24:10,650 --> 00:24:13,720
Mother?
(GASPS) You scared me.

441
00:24:13,753 --> 00:24:15,655
I scared you?

442
00:24:15,688 --> 00:24:18,124
Uh, Michael, uh...

443
00:24:18,157 --> 00:24:20,827
Michael asked me
to feed them today.

444
00:24:20,860 --> 00:24:24,063
He couldn't have.
He knew I was
coming back today.

445
00:24:24,096 --> 00:24:26,032
Well, I couldn't
possibly have known that

446
00:24:26,065 --> 00:24:28,568
since I didn't know
you'd even left.

447
00:24:29,669 --> 00:24:30,803
What?

448
00:24:32,739 --> 00:24:34,641
Lord, you must have had
an awful flight.

449
00:24:35,575 --> 00:24:37,109
Mother...

450
00:24:37,143 --> 00:24:39,178
You can't stay,
we'll talk tomorrow.

451
00:24:39,211 --> 00:24:41,113
You've got this on backwards.

452
00:24:41,147 --> 00:24:42,549
Tomorrow, Mother.

453
00:24:47,119 --> 00:24:48,955
(WHISPERS) Kathryn.

454
00:24:50,289 --> 00:24:53,192
How could you in the
middle of the afternoon?

455
00:24:55,294 --> 00:24:56,996
Haven't you got
something to tag?

456
00:24:59,265 --> 00:25:01,668
I don't believe we've met.

457
00:25:01,701 --> 00:25:03,002
Goodbye, Mother.

458
00:25:08,040 --> 00:25:09,508
I'm sure she means well.

459
00:25:09,976 --> 00:25:11,143
(DOOR OPENS)

460
00:25:11,177 --> 00:25:15,848
(LAUGHING)
You poor, sweet man.

461
00:25:15,882 --> 00:25:16,949
(DOOR CLOSES)

462
00:25:16,983 --> 00:25:19,619
That was so scary!
(LAUGHING)

463
00:25:19,652 --> 00:25:24,123
Ladies and gentleman,
there are no easy cases.

464
00:25:24,156 --> 00:25:26,726
And when you get
right down to it,

465
00:25:26,759 --> 00:25:29,929
life itself is pretty
complicated, isn't it?

466
00:25:29,962 --> 00:25:31,998
And another thing
you need to remember,

467
00:25:32,031 --> 00:25:36,168
there's a difference
between facts and the truth.

468
00:25:36,202 --> 00:25:41,708
You see, with the truth,
it requires complex elements,
such as context and intent.

469
00:25:41,741 --> 00:25:46,779
(RETCHING)
We're here, therefore, not to
simply ascertain the facts,

470
00:25:46,813 --> 00:25:48,147
but to judge the truth.

471
00:26:03,896 --> 00:26:05,197
(PANTING)

472
00:26:11,804 --> 00:26:13,272
(WATER FLOWING)

473
00:26:31,423 --> 00:26:34,326
What kind of flu makes you
throw up like that?

474
00:26:35,427 --> 00:26:37,129
Must have been
something you ate.

475
00:26:37,163 --> 00:26:39,131
Did you eat
on the airplane?

476
00:26:39,165 --> 00:26:42,368
(SCOFFS)
You know what I say
about airline food.

477
00:26:42,401 --> 00:26:46,706
It's cafeteria food
the cafeteria couldn't sell.

478
00:26:49,441 --> 00:26:51,778
If I was holding my breath,

479
00:26:51,811 --> 00:26:55,181
you'd probably just sit there
until I turned blue and died.

480
00:26:55,214 --> 00:26:56,315
Let's try it and find out.

481
00:26:56,348 --> 00:26:58,284
(DOORBELL RINGS)

482
00:26:58,317 --> 00:27:00,386
Now you stay right there,
I'll get it.

483
00:27:05,157 --> 00:27:06,292
(DOOR OPENS)

484
00:27:06,325 --> 00:27:08,427
DANIEL: Hi, I heard
she was sick.
SYLVIA: Hello. Yes.

485
00:27:08,460 --> 00:27:09,796
DANIEL: I have
these flowers for her.

486
00:27:09,829 --> 00:27:11,798
SYLVIA: I can tell her
you stopped by.

487
00:27:11,831 --> 00:27:13,432
If I could just
see her for a minute.
She has the flu.

488
00:27:13,465 --> 00:27:15,735
DANIEL: Oh, come now,
I'm sure she'll want to
see me.

489
00:27:15,768 --> 00:27:17,804
Katherine, honey,
it's Mr. Klein.

490
00:27:18,938 --> 00:27:21,173
Hey, I heard
you have the flu.

491
00:27:21,207 --> 00:27:24,711
Yes, she does and it's
extremely contagious.

492
00:27:27,479 --> 00:27:28,981
I'll find a vase.

493
00:27:35,855 --> 00:27:38,925
So why don't you, uh,
tell me where it hurts

494
00:27:38,958 --> 00:27:40,292
and I'll kiss it
and make it feel better?

495
00:27:40,326 --> 00:27:42,862
She might be right,
I could be contagious.

496
00:27:42,895 --> 00:27:44,931
There must be
something I can do.

497
00:27:44,964 --> 00:27:47,333
Well, you could take my mother
on a cruise around the world.
(DOORBELL RINGS)

498
00:27:47,366 --> 00:27:49,035
SYLVIA:
You can't go in there.

499
00:27:49,068 --> 00:27:50,336
Come back here
right this minute.

500
00:27:50,369 --> 00:27:53,172
TOM: Oh, and I'm sure
you got an engraved
invitation, huh?

501
00:27:53,205 --> 00:27:54,907
(BOTH BICKERING)

502
00:27:56,242 --> 00:27:58,444
Katherine, I...

503
00:27:58,477 --> 00:28:01,881
Great.
Tom, what are you
doing here?

504
00:28:01,914 --> 00:28:03,115
I, uh, I need
to talk to you.

505
00:28:03,149 --> 00:28:04,984
Tom, please.
SYLVIA: I told him.

506
00:28:05,017 --> 00:28:07,820
Didn't I tell you
she doesn't want any
company right now?

507
00:28:07,854 --> 00:28:11,023
I'm not company.
Kathryn, I'll just go.

508
00:28:11,057 --> 00:28:12,424
No, please, please don't.

509
00:28:15,527 --> 00:28:18,931
Well, I just brought
these things for you,

510
00:28:18,965 --> 00:28:20,499
I'd like you to try them.
Oh, you did
and they're lovely.

511
00:28:20,532 --> 00:28:22,068
Thank you. Bye.

512
00:28:22,101 --> 00:28:23,469
Sylvia, don't you have
something to tag.

513
00:28:23,502 --> 00:28:25,137
Don't you have
an ambulance to chase?

514
00:28:25,171 --> 00:28:26,773
Doesn't anyone have
anywhere else
they have to be?

515
00:28:30,843 --> 00:28:32,945
I'll check
on the flowers.
Okay.

516
00:28:36,916 --> 00:28:39,285
Oh, brilliant.

517
00:28:39,318 --> 00:28:41,120
I talked to an herbalist
in Chinatown.

518
00:28:41,153 --> 00:28:42,454
He wants to see you
right away.

519
00:28:42,488 --> 00:28:44,323
I made an appointment
for you tomorrow morning.

520
00:28:44,356 --> 00:28:45,825
What nonsense.

521
00:28:45,858 --> 00:28:48,160
She'll do nothing
of the kind. She's fine.

522
00:28:48,194 --> 00:28:49,461
No, Sylvia, she's not fine.

523
00:28:49,495 --> 00:28:51,263
Three days in bed,
she'll be back on her feet.

524
00:28:51,297 --> 00:28:53,532
Sylvia, she went to Houston
for treatments.

525
00:28:53,565 --> 00:28:56,102
That's where they send you
when they've run out of ideas.

526
00:29:05,377 --> 00:29:07,847
You don't go to Houston
for the flu.

527
00:29:16,422 --> 00:29:19,859
Mehitable called,
said there was some
kind of convention.

528
00:29:20,559 --> 00:29:22,261
Well...

529
00:29:22,294 --> 00:29:24,263
We have a quorum.

530
00:29:24,296 --> 00:29:25,331
Happy day.

531
00:29:29,135 --> 00:29:30,837
What kind of treatments,
Kathryn?

532
00:29:35,975 --> 00:29:39,879
Please tell me
you have an ulcer.

533
00:29:42,048 --> 00:29:44,250
Tell me you have a bad back.

534
00:29:46,252 --> 00:29:48,120
What is it, Kathryn?

535
00:29:50,222 --> 00:29:51,557
Chemotherapy?

536
00:29:54,994 --> 00:29:56,863
Kat, I'm sorry, I...

537
00:29:58,130 --> 00:29:59,365
You told Tom?

538
00:29:59,398 --> 00:30:01,267
No, I didn't.

539
00:30:01,300 --> 00:30:03,402
Michael, did you know?

540
00:30:10,442 --> 00:30:12,011
(WHISPERING) How dare you.

541
00:30:12,044 --> 00:30:15,047
How dare you not tell me!

542
00:30:15,081 --> 00:30:17,016
Oh, God.

543
00:30:17,049 --> 00:30:19,485
This is going to kill me.

544
00:30:19,518 --> 00:30:21,320
This will kill me.

545
00:30:21,353 --> 00:30:24,423
Oh, no. No, you do not.

546
00:30:24,456 --> 00:30:27,026
You do not make my crisis
your personal agony.

547
00:30:27,059 --> 00:30:29,896
Oh, God, did you hear that?

548
00:30:29,929 --> 00:30:33,365
She just acknowledged
that I might have some
feelings about this.

549
00:30:33,399 --> 00:30:35,601
No, Mother, I know that
you have feelings.

550
00:30:35,634 --> 00:30:38,304
There isn't a mammal in
the northern hemisphere

551
00:30:38,337 --> 00:30:40,339
that isn't personally
acquainted with your feelings.

552
00:30:40,372 --> 00:30:42,108
Sylvia, why don't...
Why don't you just
give us a moment?

553
00:30:42,141 --> 00:30:45,177
Oh, my God,
I'm so sick of both of you.

554
00:30:45,211 --> 00:30:46,913
The world's greatest experts
on my life.

555
00:30:46,946 --> 00:30:48,514
Well, I have news for you
and here it is.

556
00:30:48,547 --> 00:30:51,017
This is my disease,
do you see?

557
00:30:51,050 --> 00:30:53,019
And I'm going to handle it
the way I want to.

558
00:30:53,052 --> 00:30:57,123
If I want to puke my brains
out between verdicts,
I'm going to do that.

559
00:30:57,156 --> 00:31:02,061
If I want to beat drums
and howl at the moon,
you cannot stop me.

560
00:31:02,094 --> 00:31:06,465
This is my disease
and I'm going to do it my way.

561
00:31:06,498 --> 00:31:08,034
Judge has ruled.

562
00:31:08,067 --> 00:31:11,237
That's right. Now, you are
going to take your grandmother
to the courthouse

563
00:31:11,270 --> 00:31:13,639
to pick up her car.

564
00:31:13,672 --> 00:31:15,274
I'll come back
in the morning.

565
00:31:15,307 --> 00:31:17,643
No, Mother, you will not
come back in the morning.

566
00:31:17,676 --> 00:31:20,479
Go, and please take
Daniel with you.

567
00:31:32,291 --> 00:31:33,325
(DOOR OPENS)

568
00:31:34,493 --> 00:31:35,928
I didn't mean to do that.

569
00:31:37,129 --> 00:31:38,630
You always mean what you do.

570
00:31:42,568 --> 00:31:43,635
Go.

571
00:32:22,608 --> 00:32:24,010
(ENGINE STARTING)

572
00:32:24,043 --> 00:32:27,679
Why don't you give me
a call after you take your
grandmother home?

573
00:32:27,713 --> 00:32:29,081
No, you call me.

574
00:32:30,249 --> 00:32:31,283
I don't have your number.

575
00:32:32,351 --> 00:32:34,386
That could be a problem.

576
00:32:50,336 --> 00:32:52,171
Kathryn.

577
00:32:52,204 --> 00:32:54,206
I missed you
at choir practice.

578
00:32:55,307 --> 00:32:57,543
Listen, I heard
about your...

579
00:32:58,577 --> 00:33:00,079
If you want to talk...

580
00:33:00,112 --> 00:33:01,780
I'm perfectly fine,
but thank you.

581
00:33:01,813 --> 00:33:03,149
I went through it
with Sidney,

582
00:33:03,182 --> 00:33:05,317
he passed away
last spring.

583
00:33:05,351 --> 00:33:07,119
Sometimes you just
need a friend

584
00:33:07,153 --> 00:33:10,156
to sit and
listen to you complain
about how unfair life is.

585
00:33:10,189 --> 00:33:13,059
Well, I never thought
it was anything else.

586
00:33:28,707 --> 00:33:30,209
(KNOCKING)

587
00:33:35,814 --> 00:33:37,683
(KNOCKING CONTINUES)

588
00:33:45,491 --> 00:33:47,426
I didn't even know
you were wearing a wig.

589
00:33:49,828 --> 00:33:52,131
I know this isn't the place,
but we need to talk.

590
00:33:52,164 --> 00:33:53,399
No, we don't.

591
00:33:53,432 --> 00:33:54,533
Kathryn.

592
00:33:54,566 --> 00:33:55,767
Marion.

593
00:33:57,103 --> 00:33:59,438
I want to help,
what can I do?

594
00:33:59,471 --> 00:34:01,473
Do you really
want to help?
Of course.

595
00:34:01,507 --> 00:34:04,210
Then shut up about it.
Go away.

596
00:34:04,243 --> 00:34:06,312
Nothing is happening,
nothing out of the ordinary.

597
00:34:06,345 --> 00:34:10,449
It's a tiny blip
on the radar screen
that will soon be gone.

598
00:34:10,482 --> 00:34:12,751
Oh, this is
so typical of you.

599
00:34:13,752 --> 00:34:14,820
Good.

600
00:34:15,821 --> 00:34:17,689
I want to be typical of me.

601
00:34:27,566 --> 00:34:29,301
(TIRES SCREECH)

602
00:34:29,335 --> 00:34:30,802
(HORN HONKING)

603
00:34:30,836 --> 00:34:32,671
(ENGINE SPUTTERING)
(HORNS HONKING)

604
00:34:47,619 --> 00:34:49,155
MAN: Lady!

605
00:34:50,889 --> 00:34:52,591
WOMAN: Move your car!

606
00:36:14,506 --> 00:36:15,807
Katherine.

607
00:36:20,946 --> 00:36:22,548
What are you doing here?

608
00:36:24,983 --> 00:36:26,552
It's business, really.

609
00:36:27,753 --> 00:36:28,820
Oh.

610
00:36:31,690 --> 00:36:32,891
Well...

611
00:36:44,603 --> 00:36:46,872
Yeah, believe me,
you are not going to miss it.

612
00:36:47,773 --> 00:36:49,575
Yeah.

613
00:36:49,608 --> 00:36:53,245
Take it to Tuddle Automotive
on Habergham.

614
00:36:54,413 --> 00:36:56,214
Mmm-hmm, that's the one.

615
00:36:57,649 --> 00:36:59,851
I don't know.
It just, it stopped.

616
00:37:01,887 --> 00:37:03,955
No, I know they don't,
but this one did.

617
00:37:06,758 --> 00:37:08,026
I don't know what she did.

618
00:37:08,059 --> 00:37:10,396
She took a chainsaw
to the drive frame,
what do you think?

619
00:37:13,332 --> 00:37:14,766
It was a joke.

620
00:37:15,934 --> 00:37:17,403
Well, it wasn't meant
to be funny.

621
00:37:20,706 --> 00:37:22,341
Actually, it was meant
to make you feel stupid,

622
00:37:22,374 --> 00:37:24,710
but I realize now
I didn't have to try so hard.

623
00:37:30,482 --> 00:37:31,883
Okay, thanks.

624
00:38:04,816 --> 00:38:06,017
Thanks.

625
00:38:24,503 --> 00:38:26,372
(KATHRYN LAUGHING)

626
00:38:52,764 --> 00:38:54,866
There you are.
I've been looking
everywhere for you.

627
00:38:56,067 --> 00:38:58,437
I have some news.
Hmm.

628
00:38:59,571 --> 00:39:01,873
I made the short list,
court of appeals.

629
00:39:03,675 --> 00:39:05,677
Oh, that's great.

630
00:39:06,912 --> 00:39:09,815
I, uh, guess this calls
for a celebration.

631
00:39:10,682 --> 00:39:13,151
I am excited, I really am.

632
00:39:13,184 --> 00:39:14,986
I'm sorry, Marion.

633
00:39:17,188 --> 00:39:20,926
You don't know
how many times
I almost told you.

634
00:39:20,959 --> 00:39:25,897
I was just upset because
you did such a damn good
job of fooling me.

635
00:39:25,931 --> 00:39:28,834
But, you know, it's all
really completely up to you.

636
00:39:29,935 --> 00:39:31,136
Thanks.

637
00:39:32,638 --> 00:39:33,705
It's for you.

638
00:39:36,608 --> 00:39:37,909
(SIGHS)

639
00:39:37,943 --> 00:39:39,545
Congratulations.

640
00:39:39,578 --> 00:39:42,013
I really am proud of you.

641
00:39:42,047 --> 00:39:43,649
I really want
that job, Marion,

642
00:39:43,682 --> 00:39:45,383
I know I'd be good at it.

643
00:39:48,920 --> 00:39:51,557
KATHRYN: No, it needs to be
a transitional piece.

644
00:39:51,590 --> 00:39:54,693
The length my hair will be
in about six months.

645
00:39:54,726 --> 00:39:58,063
BRUCE: Well, this one's
very in. Not too in.

646
00:39:58,897 --> 00:40:00,766
Mmm-mmm, too Hillary.

647
00:40:01,967 --> 00:40:04,035
What about this one?
Ah!

648
00:40:04,069 --> 00:40:06,538
It would look like I was
wearing a football helmet
in that.

649
00:40:06,572 --> 00:40:09,508
That could be an advantage,
especially in your family.

650
00:40:09,541 --> 00:40:12,844
Oh, my God, Michael,
look at this.
This looks like Jamie.

651
00:40:12,878 --> 00:40:15,647
It is Jamie.
This is the wig he
wears in his show.

652
00:40:20,786 --> 00:40:22,588
Why don't you just keep
the ones you got?

653
00:40:22,621 --> 00:40:25,090
They look like
your real hair.

654
00:40:25,123 --> 00:40:27,593
Honey, they're not like
my real hair now.

655
00:40:30,496 --> 00:40:31,663
Right. It's uh...

656
00:40:32,931 --> 00:40:34,165
Shorter.

657
00:40:36,668 --> 00:40:38,937
Did we put money
in the meter?

658
00:40:40,872 --> 00:40:42,440
(DOOR OPENS)

659
00:40:54,920 --> 00:40:56,021
Isn't that Michael?

660
00:41:00,191 --> 00:41:02,193
I'll, uh, I'll catch up
with you later.
Okay. Bye.

661
00:41:08,800 --> 00:41:10,335
Michael.

662
00:41:10,368 --> 00:41:13,505
Your mother's car will be
ready tomorrow, you need
to take her down there.

663
00:41:13,539 --> 00:41:16,007
And mention my name.
Tuddle gives me
a break on the parts.

664
00:41:19,578 --> 00:41:20,912
You got a quarter?

665
00:41:38,564 --> 00:41:39,598
You need anything?

666
00:41:40,799 --> 00:41:42,568
Oh, I get it.

667
00:41:42,601 --> 00:41:44,570
Trying to be dad right now.

668
00:41:44,603 --> 00:41:46,605
Excuse me, I...
I didn't recognize it.

669
00:41:47,072 --> 00:41:48,774
You know what?

670
00:41:48,807 --> 00:41:51,577
I am not the cause of every
single problem in your life.

671
00:41:51,610 --> 00:41:53,244
No. No, you're right.

672
00:41:53,278 --> 00:41:56,715
You gave me
everything a boy could expect
from one weekend a month

673
00:42:16,101 --> 00:42:17,736
KATHRYN: All right?
I'm all right.

674
00:42:17,769 --> 00:42:19,037
Put it over there.
I'm going to let it go now.

675
00:42:19,070 --> 00:42:20,271
Okay, I got it.

676
00:42:20,305 --> 00:42:21,607
Got it?
Uh-huh.

677
00:42:22,173 --> 00:42:23,609
Not too bad.

678
00:42:27,078 --> 00:42:28,146
What's wrong?

679
00:42:28,179 --> 00:42:29,347
(GASPS) Oh, my God!

680
00:42:29,380 --> 00:42:30,849
(LAUGHS)

681
00:42:30,882 --> 00:42:32,684
Oh, my God,
look at me.

682
00:42:32,718 --> 00:42:33,885
(CHUCKLES) Oh, my God,

683
00:42:37,388 --> 00:42:38,857
(CHUCKLES)

684
00:42:45,897 --> 00:42:47,198
I'm sorry.

685
00:42:49,635 --> 00:42:51,670
It must be really weird.

686
00:42:53,672 --> 00:42:54,840
No, no, I...

687
00:42:54,873 --> 00:42:56,341
(MUMBLES INCOHERENTLY)

688
00:42:56,374 --> 00:42:58,710
You look great.

689
00:42:58,744 --> 00:43:00,846
Uh, where are those lights?

690
00:43:00,879 --> 00:43:02,714
Actually, you know...

691
00:43:05,984 --> 00:43:08,119
Actually, I think
I'd rather not.

692
00:43:08,153 --> 00:43:11,690
Well, if you're tired,
I can do it,
you can just direct me.

693
00:43:11,723 --> 00:43:15,827
No, you've been a really
big help, but I think
you should probably go.

694
00:43:15,861 --> 00:43:19,297
That's okay,
so I'll call you tomorrow,
see you at work.

695
00:43:19,330 --> 00:43:21,232
I don't think so, no.

696
00:43:25,103 --> 00:43:26,171
Oh.

697
00:43:31,409 --> 00:43:32,844
Kathryn.

698
00:43:34,279 --> 00:43:37,048
I can do this if you let me.

699
00:43:37,082 --> 00:43:40,385
I want to be here for you.

700
00:43:40,418 --> 00:43:44,389
I thought about it a lot,
and I never brought it up
because...

701
00:43:44,422 --> 00:43:45,791
I know.

702
00:43:48,426 --> 00:43:50,829
This doesn't fit anymore.

703
00:43:52,330 --> 00:43:53,832
I'm sorry.

704
00:45:08,173 --> 00:45:09,707
(CAT MEOWS)

705
00:45:43,875 --> 00:45:46,845
Oh, Mother, you weren't
supposed to open that.

706
00:45:47,879 --> 00:45:49,214
Why can't you wait
until Christmas?

707
00:45:49,247 --> 00:45:51,216
You never have
anything to open.

708
00:45:51,249 --> 00:45:53,251
You just sit there
like a bump on the log

709
00:45:53,284 --> 00:45:55,053
while everybody else
opens their presents.

710
00:45:55,086 --> 00:45:56,454
It's not any fun!

711
00:45:56,487 --> 00:45:58,790
I'll decide
what's fun for me.

712
00:45:58,824 --> 00:45:59,891
Thank you very much.

713
00:45:59,925 --> 00:46:01,059
Here.

714
00:46:04,429 --> 00:46:05,463
Wait a minute.

715
00:46:06,965 --> 00:46:08,399
I gave you this.

716
00:46:08,433 --> 00:46:10,869
You can't give it
back to me.

717
00:46:10,902 --> 00:46:15,273
(CHUCKLES) Swap with
your cousin Charlotte, then.

718
00:46:15,306 --> 00:46:20,045
You know, I thought maybe
if you wanted, you could,
uh, invite that, um...

719
00:46:22,113 --> 00:46:24,182
Your afternoon gentleman?

720
00:46:27,518 --> 00:46:31,222
I thought
maybe we could just keep it
to family this year, Mother.

721
00:46:32,223 --> 00:46:34,059
You mean you and me
and Michael?

722
00:46:35,193 --> 00:46:37,595
I was thinking
we might ask Tom.

723
00:46:37,628 --> 00:46:39,064
(DOG BARKING)

724
00:46:39,097 --> 00:46:41,232
Over my dead body.

725
00:46:41,266 --> 00:46:43,801
Oh, the dog.
Oh, that dog!

726
00:46:46,237 --> 00:46:48,073
It's what I really want, Mom.

727
00:46:48,106 --> 00:46:49,474
(BARKING CONTINUES)

728
00:46:52,577 --> 00:46:53,979
Well...

729
00:46:59,217 --> 00:47:00,451
(COUGHS)

730
00:47:25,676 --> 00:47:27,145
(DIALING)

731
00:47:27,612 --> 00:47:30,081
(TONE RINGING)

732
00:47:30,115 --> 00:47:31,316
You've reached 
 Dr. Hurley's office.

733
00:47:31,349 --> 00:47:33,251
Our regular 
 office hours... 
(PHONE BEEPS)

734
00:47:35,453 --> 00:47:36,955
(MUMBLES)

735
00:47:37,588 --> 00:47:38,623
(DIALING)

736
00:47:43,594 --> 00:47:44,862
(TONE RINGING)

737
00:47:47,132 --> 00:47:49,000
Hi, you reached 
 Tom Ainsworth.

738
00:47:49,034 --> 00:47:51,202
Please leave a message 
 at the beep. 
(PHONE BEEPS)

739
00:47:51,236 --> 00:47:52,437
It's me, Kat.

740
00:47:53,271 --> 00:47:54,872
Are you there?

741
00:47:57,943 --> 00:48:00,045
I'm really just calling to
say merry Christmas.

742
00:48:01,146 --> 00:48:02,880
Merry Christmas.

743
00:48:04,149 --> 00:48:05,283
Bye.

744
00:48:05,316 --> 00:48:06,952
(PHONE BEEPS)

745
00:48:16,995 --> 00:48:18,263
